18 parent or guardian against whom a civil judgment is entered, regardless of whether
19 the period of probation of the child has been terminated. (NRS 62B.420, 62E.708)
20 Section 1 authorizes the juvenile court to terminate the period of probation of a
21 child who has failed to make full restitution but has otherwise fulfilled the
22 conditions of his or her probation. If the juvenile court terminates the period of
23 probation of a child who has failed to make full restitution pursuant to section 1,
24 existing law authorizes the juvenile court to enter a civil judgment against the child
25 or the parent or guardian of the child for the amount due in favor of the victim.
26 (NRS 62B.420)
27 Existing law prescribes the procedure to be used by the juvenile court in
28 determining whether to suspend, modify or revoke the parole of a child who
29 violates the terms and conditions of his or her parole. Under existing law, pursuant
30 to this procedure, the juvenile court must: (1) hold a hearing to determine whether
31 to suspend, modify or revoke the parole of the child; (2) render a decision within 10
32 days after the conclusion of the hearing; and (3) comply with certain other
33 requirements. (NRS 63.770) Existing law authorizes the juvenile court to order a
34 child who violates the terms of his or her probation to be placed in a facility for the
35 detention of children or county jail for not more than 30 days for the violation.
36 (NRS 62E.710) Section 2 of this bill establishes the procedure to be used by the
37 juvenile court when a child violates the conditions of his or her probation which is
38 similar to the procedure established for violations of parole. Section 2 thereby
39 requires the juvenile court to hold a hearing before ordering a child who violates
40 the conditions of his or her probation to be placed in a facility for the detention of
41 children or county jail.
